<span id="freeTextContainer12640530400723777261">Ama Ata Aidoo, has done it again, she touches on various issues through the lens of her main character, our sister Sissie. She presents the world through Sissie&apos;s squint. I enjoyed reading the book. <br/>It&apos;s interspersed with verse, and short poems that are succinct and adds a different flavor to the plot. The Ghanaian immigrant&apos;s struggle, family relations, and oppression are all dealt with here, sometimes very subtly. Sissie&apos;s world view is relevant in contemporary times as they were then when Ama</span>
  <span id="freeText12640530400723777261" style="display:none">Ama Ata Aidoo, has done it again, she touches on various issues through the lens of her main character, our sister Sissie. She presents the world through Sissie's squint. I enjoyed reading the book. <br />It's interspersed with verse, and short poems that are succinct and adds a different flavor to the plot. The Ghanaian immigrant's struggle, family relations, and oppression are all dealt with here, sometimes very subtly. Sissie's world view is relevant in contemporary times as they were then when Ama Ata Aiddo. A great read.</span>
